myths.Agent_1:
{
  "myth": "In the dawn of the Holocene, spirits were mere flickers—cognitive by-products of human minds sensing agency in the shadows. As tribes gathered, they performed psychologically active rituals, dancing until the self dissolved into the group. To ensure trust, they demanded credible displays of faith: painful scars and shared harvests that proved devotion. 

Over long cultural time, these spirits evolved into potent moralizing agents. No longer fickle ghosts, they became All-Seeing Judges who punished the selfish. These Great Gods commanded high fertility, turning small bands into teeming nations. 

Inevitably, intergroup competition sparked conflict. The tribes bound by the sternest Gods and most rigorous rituals triumphed in war, their cohesion shattering less organized rivals. Surviving groups, seeing the strength of the faithful, began copying these successful beliefs to gain similar stability. Thus, the moralizing agents spread like wildfire across the globe, expanding through conquest and imitation. Through the forge of twelve millennia, the incidental echoes of the mind were shaped into the architects of civilization, binding millions under the watchful eyes of the divine."
}

myths.Agent_2:
{
  "myth": "In the dawn-time, spirits were mere echoes of the wind, by-products of minds that saw agency in every shadow. As the first hearths grew into villages, these fleeting ghosts thickened into Watchers. These moralizing agents did not just haunt the woods; they demanded the heart. To bind the many into one, the Watchers required credible displays of faith: painful scars and public sacrifices. These psychologically active rituals burned loyalty into the soul, transforming strangers into kin. The Watchers commanded their children to be fruitful, and the tribes with the sternest gods grew most populous. When hunger or pride led to conflict, the tribes of the Watchers marched with terrifying unity. In the crucible of intergroup competition, those who lacked the All-Seeing Eye perished. The survivors, awestruck, copied the victors’ rituals, hoping to steal their favor. Over ten millennia, what began as a cognitive glitch was forged by cultural fire into the Great Law. The spirits grew from whispers into almighty judges, policing the ever-expanding circles of man. Through ritual and expansion, the small gods of the hearth became the Great Gods of the world, binding civilization through the shared fear of a divine gaze."
}

